The AI Revolution in Music Isn't What You Think

When people hear "AI and music," they think generation. Text-to-audio. Prompt-to-track. Suno, Udio, whatever's next.

That's real, and it's interesting. But it's not the revolution.

The actual AI revolution in music is happening at the infrastructure level, and it's going to reprice the entire asset class.

Here's what most people are missing because they're still anchored to streaming: streaming only monetizes one use of music. Listening. Passive consumption by a human with headphones on.

But music has always had more uses than that. It soundtracks video games and films and apps. It provides structure for workouts and focus sessions and meditation. It's a building block for remixing, composition, and derivative content. It's an emotional context layer for every kind of media.

Streaming priced the whole asset class around the cheapest, most commoditized use case. And that pricing stuck because there was no better infrastructure to capture the other uses.

AI changes that.

As AI agents start to dominate how we interact with the internet, they're going to be looking for music they can use — not playlists to listen to. They'll be building adaptive soundtracks for games, scoring video in real time, generating personalized audio environments for the people they serve. And they don't care about popularity. They care about clear rights, contextual accuracy, and machine-readable ownership.

A catalog built for that world looks completely different from one built for Spotify.

We've been building for that world. The rest of the industry is still optimizing for streams.

The incumbents may not make it to the other side of this transition. The infrastructure for the old model is deeply embedded. The companies that recognize the shift early and build the right rails will set the price for music for the next generation.

We think that's us.